[1]
Date: Sat 29 Jan 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters News UK, Sat 29 Jan 2005 [edited]
<http://www.reuters.co.uk/newsArticle.jhtml?type=healthNews&storyID=7472445>

Viet Nam: Sick Cambodian Woman Being Tested for Avian Influenza
---------------------------------------------------------------
A 25-year-old Cambodian woman suspected of having avian influenza is
seriously ill in a hospital in southern Viet Nam, and tests are under way
to test for the virus that has killed 10 Vietnamese recently, doctors said
on Saturday [29 Jan 2005].
A doctor at the General Hospital in Kien Giang province bordering Cambodia
told Reuters that the woman was brought in on Friday morning with a high
fever. "Her condition is critical, she is on a respirator now," said the
doctor, adding that samples had been sent to the Pasteur Institute in
southern Ho Chi Minh City for testing and results were expected in 2-3 days.
"Cambodian people often come over to our hospitals here, but this is the
1st case of suspected bird flu so far," said the doctor in Kien Giang's
capital, Rach Gia, 155 miles southwest of Ho Chi Minh City. If confirmed,
she would be the 1st person from Cambodia found to be infected by the H5N1
virus in 2005.
The virus has killed at least 42 people since 1st erupting in Asia at the
end of 2003, including 12 who died in Thailand in 2004.
The World Health Organization has said the avian influenza virus might
already have infected people in countries neighboring Viet Nam such as
Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar, but these countries lack the infrastructure or
capacity to conduct necessary surveillance. Outbreaks of the virus, which
kills about 80 percent of people it infects, were last detected in Cambodia
in September 2004. No human casualties have been reported there.
On Friday [28 Jan 2005], doctors said avian influenza has killed a man in
northern Vietnam while 4 others were being treated for the virus, bringing
Vietnam's total number of infections to 16 in the latest wave of the virus,
which started in early December 2004. Of those infected, 10 have died since
30 Dec 2004, and one has been discharged from a Hanoi hospital after he
recovered. Most of the victims are believed to have caught the virus from
infected poultry, but doctors fear it could mutate into a form that is
easily passed between people, unleashing a global human flu pandemic that
could kill millions.
